   <h1>Re: [VB] Rust Protection:  In Theory and Practice</h1>
   <b>&quot;Andre Hryn&quot; &lt;hryn_at_earthlink_dot_net&gt;</b><br/>
   <i>2000-04-04 06:21:30+00</i><br/>
   <br/>
   <pre>You're not the only one that's yawning. Your post kind of remind me of my
former '64 Sundial. Every time I started something it looked like there is
more to it that I can handle. Don't get scared. The best thing I found out
is to get it completely sand blasted. This way you get  clean, rust and
paint free body that you can start from scratch on. Otherwise it's a step by
step process of removing, cleaning, painting and assembling back kind of
thing. Enjoy it.

Later,

Andre Hryn
hryn_at_earthlink_dot_net
http://www.inter-kiosk_dot_com/VW_Bus/
('63 Standard - Magic)
----- Original Message -----
From: Michele & Gene Cornelius <mizamook_at_sonic_dot_net>
To: <vintagebus_at_type2_dot_com>
Sent: Tuesday, April 04, 2000 12:58 AM
Subject: [VB] Rust Protection: In Theory and Practice


> I am hoping this post doesn't end up being a confession.
>
> I have been mulling it over, and I've decided to be somewhat intimidated
by
> the sheer amount of work I need to do to properly restore and protect my
'67
> Kombi.  Every part I take off for cleaning or replacement, I find
something
> new underneath/behind it.  An endless list of bushings, boots, and seals,
> rust to be neutralized in every crevice, and so many components that must
be
> removed to really do the job right.  I think the most daunting is the
> undercarriage.  After studying the condition of things under there
> (good/serviceable, but in need of P.M.), I realized that I "should by all
> means" remove the front beam for access to the light rust that is
developing
> on the underfloor above.  I don't know if I can!  My garage/shop is
already
> inundated with parts that I've been removing, and I can't just toss all
> non-VW related stuff out!  So I don't have enough space to spread my van
out
> in pieces....oh well.
>
> Anyway, to make a long post short (a little late on that one, I guess!), I
> am thinking I should (mostly for economical reasons) use Rustoleum
> "Hammerite" on the underfloor, where the rust isn't really bad, it's just
> there....and use the expensive POR-15 on critical spots, or where there is
> really some damage  (like the door I just bought....it's really gonna be a
> fun one!_at_#!*%$!   On the inside of the wheelwells will also be some kind
of
> rubberized undercoating.
>
> I'll quit yammering and go to bed.
>
> Later,  Gene
>
>
> -------------------------------------------------------------------------
> For help leaving the list, send a HELP message to
> VINTAGEBUS-REQUEST_at_TYPE2.COM
> -------------------------------------------------------------------------
>
></pre>


